        "body": "A heatwave that would have been \"virtually impossible\" 50 years ago killed 1,300 Europeans in ten days. The continent's infrastructure — railways, power plants, highways, homes — was designed for a climate that no longer exists.\n\nFrom June 18 to June 30, a stationary heat dome parked over Europe, breaking all-time national temperature records in seven countries. At its peak on June 28, 191 million people experienced temperatures of 35°C or higher. Germany, the Czech Republic, Poland, Hungary, Slovakia, and Denmark all recorded the hottest temperatures in their national histories — while France endured its hottest day of 2026 (44.3°C) and its highest national average on record (30.0°C). Belgium's electricity market briefly traded at €1 per kilowatt-hour — a level never before seen on the continent. French nuclear reactors shut down because the rivers used for cooling were too warm. German highways buckled. British railway tracks warped. And across the continent, the elderly died in homes not designed for heat.\n\nThe June 2026 heatwave was not an anomaly. It was the latest data point in a trend that has made Europe the fastest-warming continent on Earth — heating at twice the global average rate. The question is no longer whether Europe will face more such events, but whether it can adapt fast enough to survive them.\n\n---"
