        "body": "The backlog is one problem. The other is that even when violations occur, the law's deterrents lie dormant.\n\nThe RTI Act empowers information commissions to impose penalties of up to ₹25,000 per case against public information officers who deny information without reasonable cause. In practice, this deterrent is barely used.\n\nThe CIC Annual Report for 2024-25 shows that penalties were imposed in just **1.2%** of all cases disposed of — a mere 1,252 instances. The total penalty amount collected, as recorded in the consolidated data table, was **₹453** — less than the cost of filing 45 RTI applications.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: CIC Annual Report 2024-25, page 184; Counterview analysis, June 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nTo put this in perspective:\n- Ministry of External Affairs: ₹2 collected (₹1 each from two public authorities)\n- Department of Personnel and Training: ₹79\n- Coal Ministry: ₹17\n- UT Delhi: ₹4\n- MSME: ₹1\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: Counterview.net, June 1, 2026, analysing CIC annual report data tables. Confidence: 100.\n\nThe implied deterrent value of the penalty provision — up to ₹25,000 per denial, multiplied by 58,501 denial cases — would be nearly ₹1.5 crore. The amount actually collected was ₹453. That is a 0.003% enforcement rate."
