        "type": "debate",
        "title": "The Debate",
        "body": "### The Government's Record\n\nThe government and its supporters point to several transparency achievements:\n\n- **Electoral Bonds struck down**: The Supreme Court's February 2024 judgment striking down the anonymous political funding scheme was welcomed by transparency advocates. The Court held the scheme \"violative of Article 19(1)(a)\" — the right to information.\n- **Digital governance**: Aadhaar, DBT, faceless income tax assessment, and the RBI Digital Payments Index (which rose to 516.76 in September 2025) have reduced human discretion and leakages.\n- **Lokpal complaints rising**: 389 complaints registered in 2025-26, up from 166 in 2023-24, suggesting growing public engagement with the anti-corruption body.\n- **RTI application volume**: Over 50 lakh applications in 2024-25 indicates the law remains widely used.\n- **Whistleblowers Protection Act, 2014**: Provides a legal framework for whistleblower complaints, though critics argue it is limited in scope.\n- **Prosecution wing constituted**: The Lokpal's prosecution wing was formally established in June 2025, after 11 years.\n\n**Official Statement / Verified Fact.** Source: Lok Sabha statements by Union Minister Jitendra Singh, March 2026; Supreme Court judgment in ADR v. Union of India, February 15, 2024; PIB releases. Confidence: 100.\n\n### The Critics' Case\n\nCivil society organisations, opposition parties, and independent analysts raise systemic concerns:\n\n**1. RTI has been systematically weakened**\n\n- The 2019 amendments to the RTI Act ended the fixed five-year terms of information commissioners and removed their parity with Election Commissioners — reducing the independence of transparency bodies.\n- The DPDP Act, 2023, through Section 44(3), amended RTI Section 8(1)(j) — removing the \"unwarranted invasion of privacy\" qualifier. The public interest carve-out remains but at a higher threshold, making it harder to access information.\n- Fee revision (proposed ₹50 in 2024) was deferred after backlash but could be revived.\n- The CIC has been headless 7 times in 11 years — always due to the government failing to appoint before a known retirement date.\n\n**Expert Opinion.** Source: Frontline, October 14, 2025 — \"RTI at 20: India's Transparency Law on Life Support\"; BTI 2026 country report; Counterview, June 2026. Confidence: 95.\n\n**2. Information Commissions are deliberately understaffed**\n\n- Despite Supreme Court directions in Anjali Bhardwaj v. UoI (2019) that vacancies must be filled 1-2 months before they arise, not a single state complied fully.\n- As of January 2026, the SC was still hearing a contempt-like petition on CIC vacancies, with the government having issued an advertisement but made no appointments.\n- Uttar Pradesh — India's most populous state — had 7 of 11 commissioner posts vacant.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: Supreme Court hearing records, February 2026; SNS Report Card; LawChakra, February 10, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\n**3. The Lokpal is structurally non-functional**\n\n- \"After some years of steady improvement on this issue, India's score on Transparency International's Corruption Perceptions Index declined again after 2019, falling from 41 to 39 in 2023. The Lokpal anti-corruption authority was formed in 2019 after a six-year delay. Critics say it has proved to be a toothless organization.\" — BTI 2026 India Country Report.\n- A parliamentary committee in March 2026 asked the Lokpal to clarify its roadmap for making the inquiry and prosecution wings functional — 12 years after the Act was passed.\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: BTI 2026; Parliamentary Standing Committee 160th Report, March 2026. Confidence: 95.\n\n**4. Journalist and activist killings with impunity**\n\n- The Committee to Protect Journalists recorded India among countries that \"persistently failed to secure justice for journalists' murders.\"\n- RTI activists have been murdered with impunity. Dozens of RTI users and activists have been killed since the Act's introduction, and hundreds assaulted or harassed, according to Freedom House.\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: CPJ, February 25, 2026; Freedom House, Freedom in the World 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\n### Where There Is Agreement\n\nBoth the government and transparency advocates agree on several specific points — and what they agree on points directly to the nature of reform needed:\n\n**1. Digital governance has reduced petty corruption.** The shift to Aadhaar-linked Direct Benefit Transfers eliminated an estimated ₹1.8 lakh crore in fake beneficiaries between 2013 and 2025, according to government data. Civil society audits broadly confirm this trend. The disagreement is whether this addresses grand corruption or merely shifts it.\n\n**2. The Electoral Bonds scheme was a transparency setback.** The Supreme Court unanimously struck it down as violative of Article 19(1)(a). The State Bank of India's subsequent data disclosure provided the most detailed picture of political funding in Indian history. Both sides accept the judgment as settled law.\n\n**3. India's legal framework is adequate in design.** The RTI Act, Lokpal Act, and Whistleblowers Protection Act together create a comprehensive architecture. The problem is universally acknowledged to be implementation, not legislation.\n\n**4. Information Commissions need independence and capacity.** No party disputes that the current vacancy rates and backlog are unsustainable. The divergence is over whether the understaffing is deliberate or a capacity constraint.\n\n**Consensus Assessment.** Confidence: 90.\n\nThe implication: Reform does not require new laws. It requires filling existing vacancies, funding existing institutions, and enforcing existing penalties. The political will to do so — or the lack of it — is what separates the government's record from its stated objectives."
