        "title": "The Bigger Picture",
        "body": "### The RTI Act: A Short History of Hope and Decline\n\nThe Right to Information Act was passed unanimously by both Houses of Parliament on May 11, 2005, and received presidential assent on June 21, 2005. It was the culmination of a grassroots movement led by the National Campaign for People's Right to Information (NCPRI), the Mazdoor Kisan Shakti Sangathan (MKSS), and activists like Aruna Roy and Anna Hazare.\n\n**Historical Record.** Source: RTI Act, 2005; PRS India; historical accounts of the RTI movement. Confidence: 100.\n\nThe Act's architecture was radical for India:\n- Any citizen could demand information from any public authority\n- Time-bound response within 30 days (48 hours for life and liberty matters)\n- Independent Information Commissions at Centre and state levels\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\nFor the first decade, the system worked reasonably well. Information Commissions were functional, penalties were occasionally imposed, and a culture of transparency began to take root. The Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) used RTI-sourced information in its reports. Investigative journalists built stories on RTI-obtained documents.\n\nThe decline began around 2014-15, as administrative spending on MGNREGA was cut, the RTI Act was amended to reduce commissioner independence, and vacancies in Information Commissions went unfilled for longer periods.\n\n**Expert Analysis.** Source: Drèze & Rahul R, \"A Short History of MGNREGA\" (administrative cost patterns); Frontline, October 2025; BTI 2026. Confidence: 90.\n\n### The Economic Cost of Perceived Corruption\n\nHow much does a CPI score of 39 cost India? While precise quantification is difficult, multiple studies indicate:\n\n- **Foreign direct investment**: Countries with CPI scores below 50 attract disproportionately less FDI. A 2018 IMF working paper found that a 1-point improvement in CPI correlates with a 0.5% increase in FDI inflows relative to GDP.\n- **Sovereign borrowing**: The corruption premium in sovereign bond yields has been estimated at 20-50 basis points for countries in India's CPI range.\n- **Domestic investment**: The World Bank's Enterprise Surveys consistently rank corruption among the top three constraints for Indian businesses.\n- **Tax compliance**: Perceived corruption reduces voluntary tax compliance, creating a self-reinforcing cycle.\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: IMF Working Paper WP/18/227; World Bank Enterprise Surveys; Transparency International cost-of-corruption analysis. Confidence: 80.\n\n### What Other Countries Did Right\n\nSeveral countries have made measurable progress on the CPI since 2012:\n\n- **Estonia**: Rose from 64 (2012) to 76 (2025) — digital governance + strong independent anti-corruption agency\n- **South Korea**: Rose from 56 to 64 — sustained institutional reform after the 2016 presidential impeachment\n- **Seychelles**: Rose from 52 to 71 — comprehensive anti-corruption strategy with international monitoring\n- **Maldives**: Rose from 31 to 39 — institutional reforms after democratic transition\n\nThe common thread: sustained institutional investment, not episodic crackdowns.\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: Transparency International, CPI 2025 long-term trends analysis. Confidence: 85.\n\n### The Political Economy of Transparency\n\nIndia's transparency crisis is not a technical problem. It is a political one. Information Commissions are not underfunded by accident. The Lokpal is not dysfunctional through neglect. The RTI Act was not weakened by oversight. Each reflects a deliberate choice by the executive branch to reduce accountability mechanisms that could be used against it.\n\nAs the BTI 2026 report notes: \"The fight against corruption and bureaucratic inefficiency has long been prominent on Modi's agenda. However, after some years of steady improvement on this issue, India's score on Transparency International's Corruption Perceptions Index declined again after 2019.\"\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: BTI 2026 India Country Report. Confidence: 90."
