        "body": "### Immediate (July-September 2026)\n\n- **CIC appointments**: The Supreme Court continues to oversee the case on CIC vacancies. The next hearing could result in timelines for filling all 11 commissioners' posts.\n- **RTI fee proposal**: The government's ₹50 application fee proposal could resurface. If implemented, it would represent a 500% increase in the cost of filing an RTI.\n- **DPDP Rules implementation**: The full impact of the DPDP Act's amendment to RTI §8(1)(j) will become clearer as Information Commissions begin adjudicating cases under the new framework.\n\n### Short Term (FY 2026-27)\n\n- **Lokpal inquiry wing**: The parliamentary committee has demanded a roadmap within six months for operationalising the inquiry and prosecution wings. The government has not yet committed to a timeline.\n- **State portal upgrades**: Pressure from the CIC and civil society may push more states toward functional RTI portals. The next SNS report card will measure progress.\n- **Electoral Bonds aftermath**: The State Bank of India's disclosure of Electoral Bond data has provided the most detailed picture of political funding in Indian history. Analysis of this data will continue to shape the transparency debate.\n\n### Medium Term (2027-2029)\n\n- **CPI trajectory**: India's score is unlikely to move significantly unless institutional reforms are implemented. Historical data suggests even sustained reform takes 5-8 years to register in perception indices.\n- **RTI Act reform**: Proposals for strengthening the RTI Act — including protecting commissioner independence, mandating time-bound appointments, and increasing penalty provisions — may gain legislative traction if civil society mobilisation continues.\n- **Whistleblower protection**: The limited scope of the 2014 Act may be revisited, particularly given international pressure (the CPI report noted India as dangerous for journalists, a category that directly affects TI's scoring methodology).\n\n### Long Term (2030+)\n\n- **Generational change**: Younger Indians, who have grown up with RTI and digital governance, may demand higher standards of transparency. The CPI 2025 noted that \"widespread frustration over weak governance and limited accountability triggered protests across several countries in 2025, particularly among younger populations.\"\n- **Convergence with DPDP**: The tension between the Right to Information and the Right to Privacy (now codified in the DPDP Act) will need legislative resolution. The courts may play a defining role in balancing the two rights.\n- **Viksit Bharat @2047**: The government's long-term vision document emphasises governance reform, but whether this translates into institutional strengthening of transparency bodies remains to be seen."
