        "title": "The System",
        "body": "To understand what changes, first understand how the old machine worked.\n\nUnder MGNREGA, the system was **demand-driven**. A rural household could demand work by submitting Form-6 — written, oral, or eventually digital. Once demanded, the government was legally obligated to provide employment within 15 days. If it failed, the household was entitled to an unemployment allowance. The budget followed demand: Section 23 of the 2005 Act appropriated funds \"as may be required,\" meaning no fixed ceiling existed.\n\n**Historical Record.** Source: MGNREGA Act, 2005, Section 23; Parliamentary budget documents, various years. Confidence: 100.\n\nMoney flowed from the Centre to states on a 90:10 cost-sharing basis. The Union government bore 100% of wage costs and 75% of material costs. States paid the remaining 10%. Gram panchayats implemented at least 50% of works. Wages were paid via Direct Benefit Transfer to bank or post office accounts. Social audits were mandated but unevenly enforced.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: MGNREGA Act, 2005; CAG reports on MGNREGA implementation. Confidence: 100.\n\nHere is how VB-G RAM G changes each part of this machine:\n\n| Component | MGNREGA (Old) | VB-G RAM G (New) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Entitlement | Demand-driven; budget followed demand | Supply-driven; centrally determined allocation |\n| Funding ratio | 90:10 (Centre:State) for most states | 60:40 for general states; 90:10 for NE/Himalayan; 100% for UTs |\n| Wage guarantee | 100 days per household per year | 125 days per household per year |\n| Wage floor | No statutory national floor | ₹300/day interim national floor |\n| Budget provision | \"As may be required\" (no fixed ceiling) | Normative allocation based on objective parameters |\n| Seasonal exclusion | None | Up to 60 non-working days during peak agriculture |\n| Attendance | Manual muster rolls (later e-muster) | Face-authentication mandatory |\n| Unemployment allowance | 1/4th wage for first 30 days, 1/2 thereafter | Same (retained) |\n| Delay compensation | No statutory provision | 0.05% per day beyond 15 days |\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: VB-G RAM G Act, 2025; MGNREGA Act, 2005; PIB FAQ, May 2026. Confidence: 100."
