        "body": "### Immediate (July-September 2026)\n\n- **Transition period**: Ongoing MGNREGA works as of June 30 carried over into the new framework. New Gramin Rozgar Guarantee Cards to be issued, replacing MGNREGA job cards.\n- **Wage notifications**: States to notify their VB-G RAM G state schemes within six months (by January 1, 2027). Twenty-four states have already notified schemes.\n- **Budget release**: ₹95,692.31 crore interim allocation released to states for transition.\n- **Political challenge**: Five opposition states continue to press resolutions against the Act. Legal challenges cannot be ruled out.\n\n### Short Term (FY 2026-27)\n\n- **First full year** of VB-G RAM G implementation. The real test: whether the 125-day guarantee is backed by adequate allocations.\n- **State fiscal stress**: States with higher rural populations and weak revenues face the 40% cost burden. Watch for delays in wage payments as states adjust to the new funding model.\n- **Normative allocation formula**: Full details of the \"objective parameters\" to be operationalised. The proportion of allocation kept aside for \"performance-linked\" distribution will determine how much flexibility states have.\n\n### Medium Term (2027-2029)\n\n- **Gramin Rozgar Guarantee Cards** fully rolled out. Face-authentication attendance becomes mandatory — digital exclusion risks to be assessed.\n- **Agricultural blackout period** implementation — which states opt to use it and for how long.\n- **Budget trajectory**: If actual allocations under VB-G RAM G fall below historical MGNREGA expenditure levels, the government will face pressure to explain how the expanded guarantee is being honoured.\n\n### Long Term (2030+)\n\n- The VB-G RAM G Act is positioned by the government as part of the **Viksit Bharat @2047** vision framework. The question: does it evolve into a more comprehensive rural livelihood programme or remain primarily a wage employment scheme?\n- **Climate resilience**: The Act's focus on water security, disaster preparedness, and natural resource management aligns with climate adaptation needs — potentially a growth area for the programme."
