        "type": "debate",
        "title": "Accountability and Citizens",
        "body": "The typical Indian citizen has no reliable mechanism to report a pothole and see it fixed within a reasonable timeframe. Centralised grievance portals exist but are poorly publicised, understaffed, and produce no binding timeline for action. A 2025 RTI-based study across 12 municipal corporations found that only 17 per cent of pothole complaints received a response within 30 days.\n\nSome states have demonstrated better models. Kerala's Suchitwa Mission deployed rapid-response road repair teams with decentralised budgets. Gujarat's Road and Building Department introduced GPS-tagged pothole tracking and contractor scorecards. In both cases, repeat complaints declined measurably."
