        "type": "explained",
        "title": "How it works",
        "body": "Tamarind seeds are a waste product of the food industry — discarded by the tonne after the pulp is harvested for cooking. The team developed a process to modify the seed powder and combine it with iron oxide, giving it magnetic properties and an electrostatic attraction to plastic particles.\n\nWhen added to contaminated water, the powder binds to suspended microplastics, forming visible clumps. A handheld magnet placed against the container wall draws the clumps out. The recovered material can then be upcycled into small useful items — the team has demonstrated tiles and coasters — preventing the plastic from re-entering the environment.\n\n**Verified Fact** — Source: The Earth Prize official solution description; multiple news reports (NDTV, Mongabay, Economic Times). Confidence: 95.\n\nThe team described the origin of the idea in a statement:\n\n> \"We came up with the solution by first being very clear about the problem we wanted to solve. Once that was clear, we started looking for materials that were already available around us. Tamarind seeds stood out because they are often treated as waste, but they have natural binding properties.\"\n\n**Official Statement** — Source: The Earth Prize press release, 29 May 2026; quoted in Mongabay India, 25 May 2026. Confidence: 100."
