        "title": "The bigger picture",
        "body": "Microplastic pollution is a rapidly growing global concern. Primary microplastics (beads, abrasives) and secondary microplastics (fragments from bottles, bags, nets, synthetic textiles) accumulate in water bodies, food chains, and human tissue. Studies have detected microplastics in Arctic ice, Himalayan rainfall, and human blood and lungs.\n\nExisting removal technologies rely on membrane filtration, which requires pumps, pressure vessels, and electricity — infrastructure that is scarce in the communities most affected by water contamination. The Plas-Stick approach is notable for substituting material chemistry for energy infrastructure.\n\nThe Earth Foundation, which runs The Earth Prize, has now reached over 21,000 students across 169 countries and territories over five competition cycles. Previous winners have been featured in Forbes, BBC, Financial Times, and Business Insider, with several teams advancing to patents, partnerships, and commercial pilots.\n\n**Verified Fact** — Source: The Earth Foundation / Earth Prize impact data, 2026. Confidence: 95."
